# Configure an NGC Development Computer for SSH Access

## Overview

This guide explains how to configure a Windows development machine to securely connect to AWS GovCloud EC2 instances using:

- AWS CLI
- AWS IAM Identity Center (SSO)
- AWS Systems Manager (Session Manager)
- OpenSSH
- VS Code Remote SSH
- X11 Forwarding (Optional)

---

# Prerequisites

Install the following software before beginning.

| Software | Required |
|----------|----------|
| AWS CLI v2 | ✅ |
| AWS Session Manager Plugin | ✅ |
| OpenSSH Client (Windows) | ✅ |
| VS Code | ✅ |
| VS Code Remote SSH Extension | ✅ |
| AWS Toolkit for VS Code | Recommended |
| Cygwin (for corporate certificates) | Optional |

---

# Step 1 - Install Required Software

## AWS CLI

Install the latest version of the AWS CLI.

Verify installation:

```powershell
aws --version
```

---

## Session Manager Plugin

Install the AWS Systems Manager Session Manager Plugin.

Verify installation:

```powershell
session-manager-plugin --version
```

---

## VS Code

Install:

- Remote - SSH
- AWS Toolkit

---

# Step 2 - Configure AWS CLI

Create the following file if it doesn't already exist:

```text
C:\Users\<username>\.aws\config
```

Example:

```ini
[profile np-vega-dev]

sso_session = np-vega-dev-test
sso_account_id = <AWS Account ID>
sso_role_name = POWERUSER
region = us-gov-west-1
ca_bundle = C:\Users\<username>\.ssh\aws_bundle.pem

[sso-session np-vega-dev-test]

sso_start_url = <Identity Center Start URL>
sso_region = us-gov-west-1
sso_registration_scopes = sso:account:access
```

### Required Values

| Setting | Description |
|----------|-------------|
| sso_start_url | AWS Identity Center Start URL |
| sso_account_id | AWS Account ID |
| sso_role_name | POWERUSER or PROJADMIN |
| region | us-gov-west-1 |

---

# Finding Your AWS SSO Information

Navigate to:

```
https://start.us-gov-west-1.us-gov-home.awsapps.com/
```

Then:

1. Select your AWS Account
2. Click **Access Keys**
3. Copy:
   - Start URL
   - Account ID
   - Region
   - Role Name

---

# Step 3 - Configure SSH

Create:

```text
C:\Users\<username>\.ssh\config
```

Example:

```sshconfig
Host np-vega-dev

    User ec2-user

    IdentityFile C:\Users\<username>\Downloads\my-key.pem

    ProxyCommand aws ssm start-session --profile np-vega-dev --target i-0123456789abcdef0 --document-name AWS-StartSSHSession

    ForwardX11 yes
    ForwardX11Trusted yes
```

Replace:

- IdentityFile
- Instance ID
- Host name

Test SSH:

```bash
ssh np-vega-dev
```

---

# Step 4 - Configure VS Code

Open:

```text
C:\Users\<username>\AppData\Roaming\Code\User\settings.json
```

Add:

```json
{
    "remote.SSH.remotePlatform": {
        "np-vega-dev": "linux"
    },

    "remote.SSH.configFile": "C:\\Users\\<username>\\.ssh\\config",

    "remote.SSH.path": "C:\\Windows\\System32\\OpenSSH\\ssh.exe",

    "remote.SSH.useLocalServer": false,

    "aws.telemetry": false,

    "aws.cloudformation.telemetry.enabled": false,

    "remote.SSH.environment": {
        "PATH": "C:/Program Files/Amazon/AWSCLIV2;C:/Program Files/Amazon/SessionManagerPlugin/bin;$PATH",
        "AWS_CA_BUNDLE": "C:/Users/<username>/.ssh/aws_bundle.pem"
    }
}
```

---

# Step 5 - Configure PATH

Ensure the Session Manager Plugin is on your PATH.

Typical locations:

```text
C:\Program Files\Amazon\SessionManagerPlugin\bin
```

or

```text
C:\Users\<username>\AppData\Roaming\Code\User\globalStorage\amazonwebservices.aws-toolkit-vscode\tools\Amazon\sessionmanagerplugin\bin
```

Verify:

```powershell
session-manager-plugin --version
```

---

# Step 6 - Corporate Certificate Bundle (NGC Only)

> **Note**
>
> This step is only required if your organization uses SSL inspection (e.g. Netskope).

Install **Cygwin**.

Run:

```bash
openssl s_client \
-showcerts \
-servername ssm.us-gov-west-1.amazonaws.com \
-connect ssm.us-gov-west-1.amazonaws.com:443
```

Extract:

- AWS Server Certificate
- Intermediate CA
- Netskope Root CA

Combine them:

```bash
cat \
ssm-us-gov-west-1_amazonaws_com.pem \
ca_ngc_goskope_com.pem \
caadmin_netskope_com.pem \
> aws_bundle.pem
```

Copy the bundle to:

```text
C:\Users\<username>\.ssh\
```

---

# Step 7 - Configure AWS_CA_BUNDLE

Temporary (PowerShell):

```powershell
$env:AWS_CA_BUNDLE="C:\Users\<username>\.ssh\aws_bundle.pem"
```

Permanent Windows Environment Variable:

| Variable | Value |
|----------|-------|
| AWS_CA_BUNDLE | C:\Users\<username>\.ssh\aws_bundle.pem |

---

# Step 8 - Login to AWS

Authenticate using AWS SSO:

```powershell
aws sso login --profile np-vega-dev
```

A browser window should open.

---

# Step 9 - Test Session Manager

```powershell
aws ssm start-session \
--profile np-vega-dev \
--target i-0123456789abcdef0
```

Expected output:

```
Starting session...
Connected.
```

---

# Step 10 - Test SSH

```bash
ssh np-vega-dev
```

SSH should automatically:

1. Start an SSM Session
2. Tunnel to the EC2 instance
3. Authenticate with the configured private key

---

# Step 11 - Connect Using VS Code

1. Open VS Code
2. Press **Ctrl + Shift + P**
3. Select **Remote-SSH: Connect to Host**
4. Choose:

```
np-vega-dev
```

VS Code should connect through Session Manager.

